{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture a 1960s programmer staring at thousands of lines of tangled code. Change one thing, and three other things break. Programs were like spaghetti — pull one strand, and the whole plate moves.",
      "title": "The Spaghetti Code Nightmare"
    },
    {
      "text": "Early programs were just instructions, one after another. Great for small tasks. But as software grew, developers drowned in complexity. Finding a bug meant tracing paths through endless mazes.",
      "title": "When Programs Outgrew Their Creators"
    },
    {
      "text": "What if code could mirror how we naturally think about the world? We don't see \"height, width, speed, accelerate, brake\" — we see \"car.\" Our brains organize reality into objects with behaviors.",
      "title": "A Radical Question"
    },
    {
      "text": "In the late 1960s, Norwegian researchers Dahl and Nygaard created Simula to model real-world systems. They bundled data and actions together into \"objects.\" A ship wasn't just numbers — it was a thing that moved.",
      "title": "Simula: The First Spark"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then came Smalltalk in the 1970s, where Alan Kay coined \"object-oriented.\" He imagined software as living cells, each responsible for its own behavior, communicating through messages. Programs became ecosystems.",
      "title": "Smalltalk's Living Software"
    },
    {
      "text": "OOP introduced a simple deal: objects hide their messy internals and expose clean interfaces. You don't need to know how a TV works inside — you just press buttons. This was encapsulation.",
      "title": "The Power of Hiding Complexity"
    },
    {
      "text": "Need a new type of object? Don't rewrite everything — inherit from an existing one and customize. Dogs and cats share \"animal\" traits but add their own. Code reuse became natural, not forced.",
      "title": "Inheritance: Building on What Exists"
    },
    {
      "text": "Different objects could respond to the same message in their own way. Tell any shape to \"draw itself\" — circles, squares, triangles all know what to do. This flexibility was polymorphism.",
      "title": "Many Forms, One Interface"
    },
    {
      "text": "By the 1990s, C++ and Java brought OOP to the mainstream. Suddenly, teams of hundreds could build massive systems. Each developer focused on their objects without breaking everyone else's work.",
      "title": "OOP Goes Mainstream"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your phone apps, video games, and web browsers all speak the language of objects. OOP didn't just change how we write code — it changed what's possible to build.",
      "title": "Why This Matters to You"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Ancient astronomers tracked planets crawling across the sky. Architects calculated areas of fields. But one thing haunted them: how do you measure something that's constantly changing?",
      "title": "The Ancient Puzzle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Drop a ball. In the first second it falls slowly, then faster, then faster still. Greek mathematicians could measure where it landed — but not how fast it was moving at any single instant.",
      "title": "The Problem of Motion"
    },
    {
      "text": "Imagine trying to catch a hummingbird's speed with a photograph. The moment you freeze it, the motion vanishes. How do you measure something that only exists in movement?",
      "title": "Freezing the Unfrozen"
    },
    {
      "text": "By the 1600s, scientists were desperate. Galileo tracked falling objects. Kepler mapped planetary orbits. They had data — mountains of it. But no language to describe how things changed.",
      "title": "A World in Motion"
    },
    {
      "text": "Newton watched an apple fall. Leibniz pondered curves on paper. Independently, both asked: what if we could zoom infinitely close to a single moment and catch change in the act?",
      "title": "Two Minds, One Breakthrough"
    },
    {
      "text": "They invented a mathematical microscope — a way to examine curves at points so close together they practically touch. They called it calculus, from the Latin for 'small stone.'",
      "title": "The Mathematical Microscope"
    },
    {
      "text": "Suddenly, engineers could calculate rocket trajectories. Doctors could model how drugs spread through blood. Economists could predict market changes. The universe became describable.",
      "title": "A Universe Unlocked"
    },
    {
      "text": "Every time you check how fast your car is going, predict the weather, or watch a video compress on your phone — calculus is working behind the scenes, capturing change itself.",
      "title": "Why This Matters Now"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "For millennia, humans looked at the staggering diversity of life — whales, hummingbirds, beetles, orchids — and assumed each was crafted individually, frozen in time since creation. Species were fixed. Unchanging. Like paintings in a gallery.",
      "title": "A World of Unchanging Species"
    },
    {
      "text": "But cracks appeared in this view. Farmers knew they could breed faster horses and sweeter apples. Fossils revealed creatures that no longer existed. If species were perfect and permanent, why did they go extinct? Why could we reshape them?",
      "title": "Troubling Questions"
    },
    {
      "text": "In 1831, a 22-year-old naturalist named Charles Darwin boarded HMS Beagle for a five-year voyage around the world. He had no idea he was about to collect the puzzle pieces that would reshape biology forever.",
      "title": "A Young Naturalist Sets Sail"
    },
    {
      "text": "On the Galápagos Islands, Darwin noticed something strange. Finches on different islands had differently shaped beaks — some thick for cracking seeds, others thin for catching insects. Same bird, different tools. Why?",
      "title": "The Finches That Changed Everything"
    },
    {
      "text": "Darwin spent twenty years connecting the dots. Animals produce more offspring than can survive. Resources are limited. Those with helpful traits survive and reproduce. Over vast time, small changes accumulate into new species.",
      "title": "Natural Selection Is Born"
    },
    {
      "text": "In 1859, Darwin published 'On the Origin of Species.' The reaction was explosive. His idea was elegant yet radical: life wasn't designed from above — it was sculpted from below, by survival itself.",
      "title": "A Book That Shook the World"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, evolution is the backbone of biology. It explains antibiotic resistance, vaccine design, and why you share 98% of your DNA with chimps. Darwin gave us the key to understanding how life writes its own story.",
      "title": "Why Evolution Matters Now"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture ancient Athens. Merchants shout contradictory claims in the marketplace. Politicians make promises that sound convincing but smell fishy. How do you know who's telling the truth?",
      "title": "Chaos in the Agora"
    },
    {
      "text": "Everyone had opinions. Everyone argued. But arguments were won by whoever spoke loudest, looked most confident, or told the best jokes. Truth? That was secondary to performance.",
      "title": "Winning vs. Being Right"
    },
    {
      "text": "This drove certain Greek thinkers absolutely crazy. Surely, they thought, there must be some way to separate genuinely good reasoning from clever-sounding nonsense.",
      "title": "A Frustrating Realization"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enter Aristotle, obsessed with patterns. He noticed that some arguments always worked — like recipes that never fail. Others fell apart under scrutiny, no matter how persuasive they seemed.",
      "title": "Aristotle's Obsession"
    },
    {
      "text": "He began cataloging these patterns like a botanist collecting specimens. \"If all men are mortal, and Socrates is a man, then...\" — he was mapping the architecture of valid thought itself.",
      "title": "Mapping Thought Itself"
    },
    {
      "text": "This was revolutionary. For the first time, reasoning had rules you could check — like math, but for arguments. You didn't need to trust the speaker; you could verify the structure.",
      "title": "Rules You Could Check"
    },
    {
      "text": "Logic became philosophy's immune system — a way to detect bad reasoning before it infected your beliefs. It didn't tell you what to think, but how to think without fooling yourself.",
      "title": "Philosophy's Immune System"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, logic powers everything from courtroom arguments to computer chips. That ancient quest to find reliable rules for thinking? It shaped how humanity reasons about anything at all.",
      "title": "Why This Still Matters"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Seu avô conta que comprava pão por centavos. Seus pais lembram quando um salário mínimo pagava o aluguel inteiro. Você olha os preços de hoje e pensa: o que aconteceu com o dinheiro?",
      "title": "O dinheiro que encolheu"
    },
    {
      "text": "Durante milhares de anos, as pessoas trocavam mercadorias diretamente. Dez galinhas por um porco. Três sacos de trigo por um tecido. Não existia \"preço\" — existia negociação entre vizinhos.",
      "title": "Antes do dinheiro de papel"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando governos começaram a imprimir dinheiro, surgiu um problema invisível: quanto mais notas circulavam, menos cada uma valia. Era como diluir suco com água demais.",
      "title": "A mágica que virou problema"
    },
    {
      "text": "No Brasil dos anos 80, os preços mudavam toda semana. Supermercados remarcavam produtos enquanto você fazia compras. Famílias corriam para gastar o salário antes que ele \"derretesse\".",
      "title": "O Brasil que remarcava preços"
    },
    {
      "text": "Imagine uma cidade onde todo mundo recebe o dobro de dinheiro amanhã. Parece ótimo, certo? Mas se a quantidade de produtos continua igual, os vendedores simplesmente cobram mais.",
      "title": "Mais dinheiro, mesmos produtos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Economistas perceberam que inflação não é os preços subindo — é o dinheiro perdendo poder de compra. Uma nota de cem reais hoje compra menos que comprava há dez anos.",
      "title": "A descoberta que mudou tudo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Governos criaram metas de inflação, bancos centrais ajustam juros, e índices como IPCA viram notícia diária. Tudo para domar esse fenômeno que afeta desde o cafezinho até seu sonho da casa própria.",
      "title": "Por que você deveria se importar"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Un niño lanza una piedra al aire. Sube, se detiene un instante, y cae. Durante miles de años, la humanidad observó esto millones de veces sin poder explicar por qué. Era simplemente \"lo natural\".",
      "title": "El misterio cotidiano"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los antiguos griegos creían que cada cosa buscaba su \"lugar natural\". Las piedras caían porque pertenecían a la tierra. El humo subía porque pertenecía al cielo. Era poesía, no ciencia.",
      "title": "Explicaciones poéticas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aristóteles sentenció: los objetos pesados caen más rápido que los ligeros. Parecía obvio. Durante casi 2000 años, nadie se atrevió a cuestionar al gran filósofo.",
      "title": "El error de Aristóteles"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuenta la leyenda que Galileo subió a la Torre de Pisa y dejó caer dos esferas de diferente peso. Cayeron juntas. El mundo antiguo se derrumbaba con cada experimento.",
      "title": "Galileo desafía al maestro"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pero faltaba la pregunta más grande: si las cosas caen hacia la Tierra, ¿por qué la Luna no se estrella contra nosotros? ¿Qué la mantiene suspendida en el cielo nocturno?",
      "title": "La Luna que no cae"
    },
    {
      "text": "Newton, según él mismo, vio caer una manzana en 1666. Pero su genialidad fue preguntar: ¿y si la misma fuerza que jala la manzana también jala a la Luna?",
      "title": "La manzana de Newton"
    },
    {
      "text": "La Luna SÍ está cayendo, constantemente. Pero también se mueve hacia adelante. Cae alrededor de la Tierra, no hacia ella. La órbita es una caída perpetua que nunca termina.",
      "title": "Una caída infinita"
    },
    {
      "text": "Newton unificó el cielo y la tierra con una sola ecuación. La misma gravedad que te mantiene en tu silla gobierna el baile de los planetas. El universo seguía las mismas reglas.",
      "title": "Cielo y tierra unidos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hoy lanzamos satélites, calculamos trayectorias a Marte y predecimos eclipses con precisión de segundos. Todo comenzó preguntando algo que parecía obvio: ¿por qué caen las cosas?",
      "title": "Por qué esto te importa"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture a 1960s computer scientist typing \"What is the weather?\" and getting an error. Early machines were brilliant calculators but hopelessly confused by human language. Words were messy, ambiguous, alive — everything computers hated.",
      "title": "When Computers Couldn't Understand Us"
    },
    {
      "text": "Engineers tried writing rules for every sentence pattern: \"If noun, then verb, then object.\" But language refused to cooperate. Sarcasm, slang, poetry — human expression laughed at their rigid flowcharts.",
      "title": "The Rule-Writing Nightmare"
    },
    {
      "text": "For decades, chatbots followed scripts like actors reading from terrible plays. Ask something unexpected and they'd crumble. \"I don't understand\" became the most honest thing computers ever said.",
      "title": "Scripted Conversations Going Nowhere"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then researchers asked: what if we stopped teaching computers rules and just showed them millions of sentences? Let them find their own patterns, like a child learning to speak by listening.",
      "title": "A Radical Idea Emerges"
    },
    {
      "text": "The breakthrough came from neural networks — systems loosely inspired by the brain. Instead of rules, they learned statistical patterns. Which words tend to follow which? What makes a sentence feel right?",
      "title": "Learning Language Like Humans Do"
    },
    {
      "text": "In 2017, a paper called \"Attention Is All You Need\" changed everything. Transformers could read entire paragraphs at once, understanding how distant words relate — like finally seeing the whole puzzle, not just pieces.",
      "title": "The Transformer Revolution"
    },
    {
      "text": "Suddenly, models could be trained on the entire internet. Billions of books, articles, conversations. They absorbed humanity's written knowledge and learned to predict what word comes next with uncanny accuracy.",
      "title": "Feeding on the World's Words"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, you can ask an AI to write a poem, debug code, or explain quantum physics in pirate speak. Machines finally learned our messiest, most human skill — and now they're getting scarily good at it.",
      "title": "Why This Changes Everything"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture mathematics in the 1800s: a wild frontier. Calculus worked, but nobody could explain WHY. Infinity was a mystical concept mathematicians used but couldn't define. The foundations were built on sand.",
      "title": "Math's Identity Crisis"
    },
    {
      "text": "Georg Cantor, a German mathematician, became obsessed with a deceptively simple question: what exactly IS a collection of things? When we say 'all even numbers,' what are we really talking about?",
      "title": "Cantor's Dangerous Question"
    },
    {
      "text": "Before Cantor, mathematicians waved their hands. 'Obviously we know what a group of objects is!' But obvious isn't rigorous. And without rigor, paradoxes lurked in the shadows, ready to collapse entire theories.",
      "title": "The Hand-Waving Problem"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cantor proposed something radical: define a SET as any well-defined collection of distinct objects. Simple? Yes. Revolutionary? Absolutely. Now mathematicians had a precise language for 'bunch of stuff.'",
      "title": "A Deceptively Simple Idea"
    },
    {
      "text": "Suddenly, infinity wasn't mystical — it was countable. Cantor showed some infinities are BIGGER than others. The infinity of real numbers dwarfs the infinity of whole numbers. Mind-bending, but now provable.",
      "title": "Taming the Infinite"
    },
    {
      "text": "Not everyone celebrated. Cantor's own teacher called his work a 'disease.' The mathematical establishment resisted. Some ideas are so fundamental, they threaten everything built before them.",
      "title": "The Backlash"
    },
    {
      "text": "But set theory won. Today, virtually ALL of mathematics — from algebra to topology to computer science — rests on this foundation. When you write code that handles collections, you're using Cantor's gift.",
      "title": "The Ultimate Foundation"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set theory gave mathematicians a universal language. Any mathematical object can be described as a set. Functions, numbers, shapes — all reducible to collections and their relationships.",
      "title": "Why You Should Care"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture a massive library with millions of index cards scattered across the floor. No labels, no order. Finding one person's phone number could take days. That was computing in the 1950s.",
      "title": "Drowning in Data"
    },
    {
      "text": "Early computers stored data on punch cards and magnetic tape. Want to find a specific record? You'd literally rewind and fast-forward through miles of tape, like finding a song on a cassette.",
      "title": "The Tape Nightmare"
    },
    {
      "text": "Businesses were exploding with data — payrolls, inventories, customer records. But accessing information was painfully slow. A simple query could tie up a computer for hours.",
      "title": "When Growth Became a Problem"
    },
    {
      "text": "In 1970, an IBM researcher named Edgar Codd had a radical thought: what if data could be organized like spreadsheet tables that could talk to each other?",
      "title": "Codd's Revolutionary Vision"
    },
    {
      "text": "His relational model was elegant — data lived in rows and columns, connected by relationships. You could ask questions in plain logic instead of writing complex search programs.",
      "title": "Tables That Think"
    },
    {
      "text": "Companies like Oracle and IBM raced to build software around Codd's ideas. By the 1980s, databases became the invisible backbone of banks, airlines, and hospitals worldwide.",
      "title": "The Database Gold Rush"
    },
    {
      "text": "Every app you use, every online purchase, every social media post — all powered by databases. They're the memory banks that make our digital world possible.",
      "title": "Why This Changes Everything"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture Paris in the 1860s. If you wanted to be a serious artist, there was only one path: paint historical scenes, mythological figures, and portraits with photographic precision. Anything less was considered amateur scribbling.",
      "title": "The Academy's Iron Grip"
    },
    {
      "text": "A group of young painters grew restless. They didn't want to spend months perfecting a Roman emperor's toga in a dimly lit studio. They wanted to capture sunlight dancing on water, the blur of a crowd, the feeling of a moment.",
      "title": "Rebels in the Studio"
    },
    {
      "text": "These artists did something radical — they packed up their easels and went outside. They painted en plein air, chasing the sun across fields and riversides, working fast before the light changed.",
      "title": "Painting in the Wild"
    },
    {
      "text": "The establishment was horrified. These paintings looked 'unfinished.' Where were the crisp lines? The smooth brushstrokes? Critics mocked a painting called 'Impression, Sunrise' — and accidentally gave the movement its name.",
      "title": "A Name Born from Mockery"
    },
    {
      "text": "Monet, Renoir, Degas, and their friends embraced the insult. They weren't trying to copy reality like a photograph. They wanted to capture how a moment FEELS — the shimmer of light, the atmosphere, the fleeting impression.",
      "title": "Feeling Over Perfection"
    },
    {
      "text": "They discovered something profound: our eyes don't see the world in sharp focus. Light vibrates, colors blend, moments blur. Their 'messy' brushstrokes were actually more true to human perception.",
      "title": "Seeing Like the Eye Sees"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, Impressionist paintings sell for hundreds of millions. But more importantly, they opened a door. Art didn't have to be about perfect representation anymore — it could be about vision, emotion, and the courage to see differently.",
      "title": "Why This Changed Everything"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Por milhares de anos, a humanidade viveu em aldeias pequenas onde todos se conheciam. As regras eram claras: você fazia o que seu pai fez, casava com quem a família escolhia, e morria na mesma terra onde nasceu.",
      "title": "Um mundo de certezas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Então, no século XVIII, máquinas começaram a rugir na Inglaterra. Camponeses abandonaram suas terras e marcharam para cidades cinzentas. Em poucas décadas, o mundo que existia há séculos se despedaçou.",
      "title": "As engrenagens da mudança"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cidades que tinham 10 mil habitantes explodiram para 100 mil. Famílias se separaram. Estranhos dividiam cortiços apertados. Ninguém mais sabia quem era seu vizinho — ou quais eram as regras do jogo.",
      "title": "O caos urbano"
    },
    {
      "text": "Revoltas estouravam. Fábricas pegavam fogo. Crianças trabalhavam 14 horas por dia. Os filósofos olhavam para aquele caos e se perguntavam: por que a sociedade funciona assim? Existe alguma lógica nisso?",
      "title": "Perguntas sem resposta"
    },
    {
      "text": "Auguste Comte teve uma ideia ousada: e se estudássemos a sociedade do mesmo jeito que estudamos planetas e reações químicas? Com método, observação e análise — não apenas opiniões.",
      "title": "Nasce uma ciência"
    },
    {
      "text": "A ideia pegou fogo. Pensadores como Durkheim, Marx e Weber mergulharam fundo nas engrenagens invisíveis que movem grupos humanos. Cada um com suas lentes, tentando decifrar o mesmo enigma.",
      "title": "Os primeiros exploradores"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hoje, quando você se pergunta por que certas músicas viralizam, por que desigualdade persiste, ou por que nos comportamos diferente online — você está fazendo sociologia. A ciência de entender nós mesmos.",
      "title": "Por que isso importa para você"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagine you're standing between two mirrors facing each other. You see yourself reflected infinitely — a copy inside a copy inside a copy. This mesmerizing effect captures something profound that programmers discovered about problem-solving itself.",
      "title": "The Infinite Mirror"
    },
    {
      "text": "Early mathematicians noticed something curious: some problems contained smaller versions of themselves. A Russian nesting doll, if you will. To count all the dolls, you just count the outer one and then... count the dolls inside. The same task, just smaller.",
      "title": "Problems Within Problems"
    },
    {
      "text": "In the 1930s, logicians like Alonzo Church were wrestling with a big question: what does it mean to compute something? They realized that any calculation could be broken down into a pattern that references itself.",
      "title": "The Logicians' Puzzle"
    },
    {
      "text": "When the first programming languages emerged, designers faced a choice: should a function be able to call itself? Some early languages said no — it seemed too dangerous, too mind-bending. Like letting a word define itself in a dictionary.",
      "title": "A Dangerous Idea"
    },
    {
      "text": "But then something clicked. Programmers realized that self-referencing functions could express solutions with breathtaking elegance. A maze? Just solve the smaller mazes within it. A family tree? Just process each branch the same way.",
      "title": "Elegance Emerges"
    },
    {
      "text": "The name 'recursion' comes from Latin 'recurrere' — to run back. And that's exactly what happens: a function runs forward, then runs back through all the smaller problems it created, gathering answers like breadcrumbs on the way home.",
      "title": "Running Back"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, recursion powers everything from search engines indexing billions of pages to the undo button in your favorite app. It's how computers think about problems that nest inside themselves — which, it turns out, is most of the interesting ones.",
      "title": "Why This Changes Everything"
    }
  ]
}
